05795nam a22009015i 9789048550371DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485503717 a10.1515/97890485503712doi  a(DE-B1597)572718  a(OCoLC)1231610346  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aDS526.4b.F37 2021 7aHIS0370302bisacsh04a959.0422300aRacial Difference and the Colonial Wars of 19th Century Southeast Asia /ced. by Farish Ahmad-Noor, Peter-Brian Ramsay Carey. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- t1 Towards the Great Divide -- t2 Hostis Humanis Generis -- t3 Piratical Headhunters yang semacam Melayu dan Cina -- t4 The Franco-Siamese War and the Russo-Japanese War -- t5 ‘Sly Civility’ and the Myth of the ‘Lazy Malay’ -- t6 ‘Smoked Yankees’, ‘Wild’ Catholics and the Newspaper ‘Lions’ of Manila -- t7 Warriors and Colonial Wars in Muslim Philippines Since 1800 -- tChronology of Major Events and Conflicts in Southeast Asia, 1800-1900 -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe colonisation of Southeast Asia was a long and often violent process where numerous military campaigns were waged by the colonial powers across the region. The notion of racial difference was crucial in many of these wars, as native Southeast Asian societies were often framed in negative terms as 'savage' and 'backward' communities that needed to be subdued and 'civilised'. This collection of critical essays focuses on the colonial construction of race and looks at how the colonial wars in 19th century Southeast Asia were rationalised via recourse to theories of racial difference, making race a factor in the wars of Empire. Looking at the colonial wars in Java, Borneo, Indochina, Philippines and other parts of Southeast Asia, the essays examine the manner in which the idea of racial difference was weaponised by the colonising powers and how forms of local resistance often worked through such colonial structures of identity politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aRace discrimination. 4aAsian Studies. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Modern / General.2bisacsh  aRace, Colonialism, Orientalism, Colonial Wars, Southeast Asia.1 aAhmad-Noor, Farish, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarey, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarey, Peter-Brian Ramsay, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMalitz, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaidu, Netusha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoor, Farish A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShott, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTan, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVartavarian, Mesrob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311068955608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074322708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2z978311074335708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz9